<br>
I just led half a raid up there with the fellowship (I went LD on the lower aggro isle <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  -- Power outage for an hour), and we did very well with a group ranging from 48-61.  The 48 was a Cleric and the 61 was a Cleric.  We used a 59 Paladin to tank (Suometar) and other than a few unfortunate accidents, it went as smooth as butter.  <br>
<br>
We went up to the Pegasus Isle and did three Paladin Epic turn-ins in about four hours, with a slight detour to do a Monk Epic fight on the Djinn isle.  We had at our max about 24 people and were whittled down to 18 because of people getting knocked off the isles, going LD for too long, RL emergencies, and lack of keys.  We also did this without corpse summoning.<br>
<br>
As that was all we had planned for the raid, we ended it there.  We will be heading up again to clear the Pegasus Isle and collect Ranger Epic pieces and to the Spiroc Isle for Warrior Epic blades in mid April, but as the Fellowship is a large organization with the manpower to do it on it's own, it will be a closed raid.  I believe I posted this already in Battlefield.<br>
<br>
What I have to say is this plane is do-able and not as bad as the guides make it out to seem.  It is a good challenge, but if you have a core group of highly seasoned people (one 58+ group) you can take about anyone up there.  Just make sure you have a group of 54+ Enchanters who will work well together to break the Imp Isle.  Other than that, you should be fine.<br>
<br>
